Part I - Prosper Loan Data Exploration¶

by (Fidelia Tubonibo)¶

Introduction¶

This dataset contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan. It explores the relationship between certain features including loan amount, loan status, borrower income, etc.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This dataset contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan. Most variables are numeric in nature, but some including the variables prosper score, listing category, income range, loan status, prosper ratings, loan origination quarter are categorical.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

This dataset explores the features that play a significant role in the loan amount disbursed .

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Features that support this investigation include;

  • Loan original amount
  • Loan status
  • Borrower's APR
  • Lender Yield
  • Year
  • Quarter
  • Listing category
  • Prosper score
  • Income range
  • Employment status
  • Home ownership
  • Total prosper loans
  • Outstanding principal
  • Borrowed principal
  • On-time prosper payments

Univariate Exploration¶

We begin by creating a visual of the loan status;

What is the frequency of each loan status?¶

In [12]:
plt.figure(figsize = [10,5])

base_color = sns.color_palette()[0]

freq = loan_df['LoanStatus'].value_counts()

# Get the indexes of the Series
gen_order = freq.index

# Plot the bar chart in decreasing order of the frequency of the `LoanStatus'
sns.countplot(data=loan_df, x='LoanStatus', color= base_color, order = gen_order)

plt.xticks(rotation=90);

The bar chart above shows that the loan outcome status with the most frequency is the current loan. Meaning about 60,000 loans were fully paid up to date . This is followed closely by completed loans with a count of about 38,000. We also note that there are no cancelled loans and a small number of loans were past due. A little over 10000 loans were charged off i.e declared uncollectable and about 5000 were defaulted loans.

Next we examine the factors that possibly affect the above loan status. We begin with the borrower APR (Annual Percentage Rate) which is the percentage of principal to be paid each year. The distribution of the APR is shown below.

plt.xlabel('Outstanding Principal')
plt.show()

Outstanding principal has a long tail distribution with most of the amount left to pay on the low end. When plotted with a log scale, the distribution is multimodal and tilted to the right indicating that there might be outliers on the left.

Bivariate Exploration¶

This section starts off with an investigation of the relationship between the two main features of interest - loan amount and loan status.

What is the relationship between loan amount and loan status?¶

In [22]:
plt.figure(figsize=[12,8])
sns.boxplot(data=loan_df, x='LoanStatus', y='LoanOriginalAmount', color=base_color)
plt.xticks(rotation=45);

The loan status with the highest loan amount is "current" with a median loan amount of 10,000 and a maximum length at 32,000. The loan status with the least amount is "cancelled". This means that a high amount of loans are yet to meet their deadline.

How often were loans given out to high risk ventures?¶

In [23]:
#The score ranges from 1-10, with 10 being the best, or lowest risk score.
plt.figure(figsize = [20,8])
sns.violinplot(data=loan_df, x='ProsperScore', y='LoanOriginalAmount', color=base_color, inner= 'quartile');

From the violin plot above, high risk prosper scores are shown to have smaller loan amounts (shown by the wide curves) as opposed to low risk prosper scores although there are a number of outliers. The low risk prosper scores have the smallest distribution of loan applications.

Do people with a high income range get more loans?¶

In [24]:
plt.figure(figsize = [10,8])
sns.stripplot(data = loan_df, x = 'IncomeRange', y = 'LoanOriginalAmount', color = base_color)
plt.xticks(rotation=45);

The stripplot above shows that people who earn 100k and above get the most loans while people who are not employed get the least with exception to a few outliers. It's safe to say that more loan is given to borrowers with high income range.
